label chapter10:

    # [Scene: Arcology Development Site | Late Afternoon]

    scene bg ch9_3be532_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Low, warm strings with a subtle steady pulse; a soft brass thread suggests ceremony]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The steady hiss of concrete pouring, distant generator hum, gulls muffled by fog]
    "You stand at the edge of the Arcology site where the seawall's foundation has become a thing you can point at and name. It is heavier than the models, heavier than the meetings; the wet concrete"
    "sighs into molds and a new line cuts the horizon. The smell of salt and fresh cement wraps around you — mineral and living — and for the first time in a long stretch of meetings"
    "and proposals, you can feel a shape of safety forming under your palms."
    "Relief blooms dull and wide under your ribs. This is not triumph; it is the practical kind of rising that takes screws and permits and long negotiations, the kind you can count in inches and in"
    "signatures. Still, it is rising. The town will not be swallowed where it stood last winter. That is a consequence you fought for, a promise you will carry."

    scene bg ch9_3be532_2 at full_bg
    show noah_vega at left:
        zoom 0.7

    noah_vega "We couldn't have it without your willingness to sign, Aria."
    hide noah_vega

    scene bg ch9_3be532_3 at full_bg
    show aria_marin at left:
        zoom 0.7

    aria_marin "We couldn't have it without Dr. Linh's conditions either."
    hide aria_marin

    scene bg ch9_3be532_4 at full_bg
    show aria_marin at left:
        zoom 0.7

    aria_marin "You read the clauses — siting, permeable sections, buffer zones. They're in the contract."
    show noah_vega at right:
        zoom 0.7

    noah_vega "And your public endorsement made the funders listen. That—"
    hide aria_marin
    hide noah_vega

    scene bg ch9_3be532_5 at full_bg
    show noah_vega at left:
        zoom 0.7

    noah_vega "—that alignment mattered."
    "His gratitude is simple and exact. It settles beside the other currents moving through this place: contracts, relocations, the quiet letters on kitchen tables. The tide of policy runs in concrete numbers; you have learned to translate that tide into a language the town can use."
    hide noah_vega

    scene bg ch9_3be532_6 at full_bg
    show kai_solano at left:
        zoom 0.7

    kai_solano "Alignment? You call it alignment when it shapes who gets to keep a home and who gets a payout? You call it alignment when whole blocks are told to fold up and leave?"
    show aria_marin at right:
        zoom 0.7

    aria_marin "Kai—"
    hide kai_solano
    hide aria_marin

    scene bg ch9_3be532_7 at full_bg
    show kai_solano at left:
        zoom 0.7

    kai_solano "Don't 'Kai—' me. I watched families get letters that mean 'find somewhere else.' You could have held out—"
    hide kai_solano

    scene bg ch9_3be532_8 at full_bg
    show kai_solano at left:
        zoom 0.7

    kai_solano "—you could have chosen the streets with us. You chose a table with people who have surety."
    show aria_marin at right:
        zoom 0.7

    aria_marin "I chose the one way that might keep more of them from losing everything. The tenant fund? Raised. The cultural corridor? Preserved as raised boardwalks. We attached covenants that limit displacement in perpetuity, Kai. That is not betrayal; it's a different kind of fight."
    hide kai_solano
    hide aria_marin

    scene bg ch9_3be532_9 at full_bg
    show kai_solano at left:
        zoom 0.7

    kai_solano "You think a covenant replaces a kitchen where a child learned to make clam soup? You think it replaces the stall that smelled like lemon and old books?"
    "Aria Marin:"
    hide kai_solano

    scene bg ch9_3be532_10 at full_bg
    show aria_marin at left:
        zoom 0.7

    aria_marin "No. It doesn't replace memory. That's why the cultural corridor exists — a raised boardwalk where those shops can continue to exist in some form. We're mitigating loss, Kai. Not pretending loss doesn't happen."
    show kai_solano at right:
        zoom 0.7

    kai_solano "Mitigation is not the same as resistance. You're softening the blow for the developers."
    "Aria Marin:"
    hide aria_marin
    hide kai_solano

    scene bg ch9_3be532_11 at full_bg
    show aria_marin at left:
        zoom 0.7

    aria_marin "And marching us into empty promises is resistance? You risk destabilizing the funding that buys buyouts for the elderly on fixed incomes. You risk the town's credit, Kai. People are counting on us to be real with them."
    "Kai Solano:"
    hide aria_marin

    scene bg ch9_3be532_12 at full_bg
    show kai_solano at left:
        zoom 0.7

    kai_solano "Real—real like paperwork that moves people a mile inland? Real like 'we'll preserve what we can' while the rest becomes a glossy case study?"
    show aria_marin at right:
        zoom 0.7

    aria_marin "I am trying to hold both realities at once. We cannot watch people drown today while we fight for ideology tomorrow."

    kai_solano "So you become the voice that tells them to accept what they can get."
    "Aria Marin:"
    hide kai_solano
    hide aria_marin

    scene bg ch9_3be532_13 at full_bg
    show aria_marin at left:
        zoom 0.7

    aria_marin "I'm asking them to accept what will keep more people housed and fed."
    show kai_solano at right:
        zoom 0.7

    kai_solano "You asked me to trust you."

    aria_marin "And I asked you to trust that policy can follow action, that we can secure protections in law."
    hide aria_marin
    hide kai_solano

    scene bg ch9_3be532_14 at full_bg
    show aria_marin at left:
        zoom 0.7

    aria_marin "I didn't sign away the town, Kai. I tried to save as much as we could in one passage."
    "Kai Solano:"
    hide aria_marin

    scene bg ch9_3be532_15 at full_bg
    show kai_solano at left:
        zoom 0.7

    kai_solano "We said we'd give everything for the town."
    show aria_marin at right:
        zoom 0.7

    aria_marin "Not everything, Kai. We promised to be careful with what people have left. Sacrifice isn't a moral aesthetic — it is a price. I couldn't ask the town to pay more than they already have."
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A long silence held between two waves; the concrete pours continue like a heartbeat]

    kai_solano "Then we are different people now."

    aria_marin "We always were different people. That doesn't mean we can't work together."
    "Kai Solano:"
    hide kai_solano
    hide aria_marin

    scene bg ch9_3be532_16 at full_bg
    show kai_solano at left:
        zoom 0.7

    kai_solano "Work together, yes. Together, not lovers, Aria. I can't—"
    hide kai_solano

    scene bg ch9_3be532_17 at full_bg
    show kai_solano at left:
        zoom 0.7

    kai_solano "—I can't watch you make deals that feel like selling souls and pretend I'm by your side in bed afterwards."
    "Aria Marin:"
    hide kai_solano

    scene bg ch9_3be532_18 at full_bg
    show aria_marin at left:
        zoom 0.7

    aria_marin "And I can't hold the town to the ideal of ruin for purity's sake."
    hide aria_marin

    scene bg ch9_3be532_19 at full_bg
    show aria_marin at left:
        zoom 0.7

    aria_marin "Promise me we'll keep fighting. Different ways, maybe. But together for the town."
    "Kai Solano:"
    hide aria_marin

    scene bg ch9_3be532_20 at full_bg
    show kai_solano at left:
        zoom 0.7

    kai_solano "Together, for the town."
    hide kai_solano

    scene bg ch9_3be532_21 at full_bg
    show kai_solano at left:
        zoom 0.7

    kai_solano "But not lovers."
    "It hurts like the honest cold of water against a bruise. That private tenderness — the nights shared over maps and the small, ridiculous jokes across coffee — is cut into a new shape by public"
    "duty. You let it cleave; you bend toward the work. The town's needs are louder than your want."
    hide kai_solano

    scene bg ch9_3be532_22 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Soft woodwind enters; a gentle, hopeful motif threads through]
    show elder_tomas_quay at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elder_tomas_quay "We gather to mark what was spared and what we must leave to make room for those who remain. This line is a map of choices. Some were painful. Some were necessary. We remember both."
    "He speaks with the deep, grainy voice of someone who has watched more tides than most can count. Around him, the crowd is a mix of relief and hollow-eyed grief; some faces are resolute, others folded"
    "into hands. A woman two rows from you dabs at her cheek with a salt-stiffened sleeve. A boy holds a model boat in both fists, oblivious and perfect."
    hide elder_tomas_quay

    scene bg ch9_3be532_23 at full_bg
    "You step forward because the ceremony asks for something outward. You reach into the satchel and close around the brass compass — your father's compass, a keepsake that has guided you back to this town and through decisions you still don't know how to forgive yourself for."

    menu:
        "Place the compass gently on the plaque":
            "You set the brass compass in the shallow circle at the plaque's base. It fits like a quiet answer. The metal is warm from your palm, and for a second the world narrows to the soft click of enclosure."
        "Trace the names first, then place the compass":
            "You run a fingertip along the first line of names, feeling the indentation like a map of loss. Only after the tracing do you place the compass, as if the gesture honors each person before the token."
        "Hold the compass to your chest and speak a quick prayer":
            "You bring the compass to your sternum and murmur a private promise. When you place it on the plaque, the motion feels like a hand returning something borrowed."

    # --- merge ---
    "Continue to the ceremony aftermath narration below."
    "Elder Tomas nods, a small, approving lift of his chin that means more than public praise. The crowd murmurs thanks to God, to the sea, to whoever keeps watch. You feel the weight of what you've"
    "done and the soft, steady lift of what you've prevented. The seawall is not salvation — no single thing will be — but it is shelter for a great many."
    # [Scene: Cultural Corridor | Dusk]

    scene bg ch9_3be532_24 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A hopeful piano motif; light strings brighten the harmony]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The boardwalk creaks; distant laughter; a kettle boiling in a distant apartment; wind through banners]
    "You walk the corridor like someone moving through a cathedral at first light. The raised planks hum underfoot; small shops you remember as child-sized and eternal lean out to the narrow promenade, their doors either closed"
    "and waiting or open with a quiet hearth. The corridor is a stitched thing — old boards repurposed, mural panels that survived an earlier tide, a line of salt-worn photographs in a glass case. It is"
    "work made visible."
    "There is victory here that does not sing. It is tidy, practical, a line of light on otherwise storm-dark water. You taste it as salt and paper and boiled coffee — survival baked into aroma. The"
    "tenant fund will be distributed. The living-shoreline pilots get funding. The corridor preserves the smells and textures of a neighborhood; it does not return demolished porches and the exact crookedness of a favorite sign. You let"
    "yourself hold both truths."

    menu:
        "Pause at the closed bookshop and peer in":
            "You press your palm to the cool glass and see your reflection among stacks of unsold stories. A flyer taped to the door lists the owner's new address inland. You step away twice, a small tender ache in your chest."
        "Sit on a bench beneath a lantern and breathe out":
            "You lower onto the bench and let the air fill your lungs until your shoulders loosen. A neighbor sits across and offers you a thermos; you accept and sip warmth into your hands."
        "Write a quick note and tuck it into a painted seam of the boardwalk":
            "You take a scrap of paper from your satchel, scrawl a promise—'We will keep this'—and tuck it into a painted seam. It feels childish, but the hope is stubborn and you like that stubbornness."

    # --- merge ---
    "Continue to the corridor narration below."
    "You choose a small thing—any small thing—and it steadies you. People you know trade quiet nods as you pass. Someone hums a refrain that you recognize from a festival before the tides got mean. It is ordinary, and therefore fragile, and therefore immensely worth guarding."

    scene bg ch9_3be532_25 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Strings resolve into a gentle, consonant chord]
    "Safety has been carved from compromise. You financed protection, anchored legal safeguards, and designed spaces that hold memory like a net. You lost as you gained; entire blocks accepted relocation and will look at Salthaven from"
    "a distance now. The town is quieter in places, yes — some shops will not reopen, and you will pass closed doors whose owners decided to leave rather than be islands in a protected future."
    "But the arc of the work bends upward. Not because nothing was taken, but because what remains is more likely to endure. Elder Tomas's voice at the plaque was a benediction and a charge: remember the"
    "cost and keep building. You feel both relief and sorrow threaded through the same breath."
    "You have done what you set out to do: build resilience in a way that kept community at the center. The victory tastes like a reserved candle in a storm — it will not erase grief,"
    "but it will allow more people to stand through the next tide. That is the kind of rising worth having."

    scene bg ch9_3be532_26 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Hopeful strings swell, then settle into a calm lullaby of light percussion and piano]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Distant, contented chatter; a bell marking the evening; a gull receding into wind]
    "You tuck the satchel closer, feel the silver band warm against your finger, and let your footsteps keep time with the town you love. You and Kai will continue to fight for Salthaven in different ways."
    "Noah will press the firm toward commitments that your signature made possible. Dr. Linh will watch the living shorelines grow; she will not spare them from critique, but she will tend them like a parent tends"
    "a fragile child. Elder Tomas will keep his stories sharp and ready."
    "It is a beginning that keeps the old stories and teaches new ones — a line drawn by engineers and elders and activists, by compromises and stubbornness alike. The arc returns upward. That return carries sorrow and relief braided tightly, but it carries forward."

    scene bg ch9_3be532_27 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Resolve chord, gentle piano; music fades slowly]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The sea breathing; footsteps receding]

    scene bg ch9_3be532_28 at full_bg
    "THE END"
